posts.name: Al Skierkiewicz  Learn Something New, Every Day!
posts.cooked: In reference of the CBA IV, the max current for our type of battery is restricted with normal software to about 12.5 amps.  The spec is actually about 150 watts.  There are accessories you can purchase that raise that raise that to 500 or 1000 watts.  However, I chose 7.5 amps and a cutoff of 10.5 volts because that test requires about 2.5 hours to complete.  It does closely match published discharge curves from several manufacturers.  At a 7.5 amp discharge, I feel a result of better than 12 amp hours indicates a good battery.  There is advanced software, (available from West Mountain Radio) that can pulse load the battery and set some other tests that will help you analyze your batteries including an impedance measurement.  I have a copy of that software and have tested it against batteries that met or exceeded good or had failed.  The results were consistent with other testing methods. Compared with the CTRE tester, the CBA obviously gives a more detailed test over time.  The CTRE test will indicate a good battery as it stands right now and the test takes seconds compared to hours.  I have no problem with CTRE tester but prefer to use the CBA for all of the other features. For one, the CBA allows you to save a test and overlay that test with other batteries or with the same battery over a period of time.  That allows you to compare battery performance and determine the current operational status of the battery.  If  battery consistently reports better than 12 amp hour, it is good enough for match play.  When it falls below that, I relegate the battery to practice only.  Another thing that the CBA will show, is battery cells that have diminished capacity in that they can only supply current for a fixed amount of time at which the battery voltage drops by 2 volts.  The display also shows when a battery, battery wiring or connector is intermittent by displaying small fluctuations in terminal voltage. I used the CBA III for many years and then bought a CBA IV.  There is a new version available CBA V.  I have not bought one yet but it is designed for 200 watt max load. West Mountain Radio - Computerized Battery Analyzer I prefer the CBA analyzers for the amount of information they give the team and the ability to compare tests and save results.  AndyMark also sells these as listed above.

posts.name: This isn't a game. Think about the repercussions.
posts.cooked:
Yes, I can elaborate on why a CBA is not ideal for lead-acid batteries. The CBA tests by discharging the battery to a user-specified voltage (typically 9.6 volts for lead-acid). This kind of deep discharge is bad for the battery. While a single test may only cause a little harm, it is still harmful. Multiple tests are multiply harmful.

A brief high-discharge test (e.g. 3 times the Ah rating for 15 seconds) is not very harmful, and had been the standard for lead-acid batteries in the 20th century. Modern testing measures the battery’s internal resistance and not only is less harmful but far more accurate at determining the battery’s ability to deliver energy - i.e. its health. And battery health is what FRC teams are interested in (along with state of charge, which is a completely different test.)

With all due respect to @Al_Skierkiewicz he’s an RF engineer with a lifetime ofexperience, and I am a battery engineer with similar experience. I love Al like a brother, and we generally agree, but I stand firm that an internal resistance test has more value than a deep discharge test in determining the condition of an FRC battery.

posts.name: Al Skierkiewicz  Learn Something New, Every Day!
posts.cooked: I agree with Don in most respects.  I am using the CBA to duplicate manufacturing testing by using a specified load to generate 7.5 amps while drawing the battery to 10.5 volts.  I chose those ratings because it allows a test to complete in less than three hours. (our normal team meeting length)  I have used other values, and longer test times to verify the battery duplicated other curves from the manufacturer’s printed documentation.  the battery is specified to be 18 AH when discharged at 1/20 of the battery discharge.  (18AH/20 = 0.9 amps)  That test lasts more than 18 hours for a good battery that is fully charged.  (I am old and don’t have that kind of time any longer.)  When teams have asked about the heavy load testers that are similar to Don’s statement above, I have suggested using other tools.  Many of those I have been questioned about, put such a heavy load on the battery I fear permanent damage.  They are generally trying to show cold cranking amps on an automotive battery capable of peak currents  that are more than twice what robot batteries are capable of. While RF was part of my job, I am a Broadcast Engineer and had to deal with everything at a TV and Radio station from lavalier mics in the studio right up to the transmitters on Sear’s Tower.  Don and I are both ham radio operators and i believe we are thinking the same things here, just from a different view.  Internal battery impedance can  be a good check on battery health.  However, it may or may not indicate a bad cell to an untrained eye. In my opinion, the CBA will give teams a simple test method that will show a clear difference from published discharge curves.  This is kind of a no brainer test but the device can be pricey for some teams.  You can’t run the quick test of a CTRE checker but you can duplicate published specs in a two hour test.

posts.name: Al Skierkiewicz  Learn Something New, Every Day!
posts.cooked: B, Yes, the CTRE tester can give a false test if one or more of the cells are degraded.  In that the moment that the test is performed it will show correct readings.  It cannot show a cell that goes bad after it is used for some time.  It is likely that the impedance test would show a difference from previous tests, if your team keeps accurate test results.  The CBA will show a cell that has depleted performance as a drop in two volts during the test.  CBA also keeps a complete record of each test (assuming you name tests differently for each battery).

posts.cooked:
Hm. No, not really. Something that draws about 3 times the Ah rating (3 * 18 = 54 Amps) for 15 seconds, monitoring the voltage at the battery terminals at the 15 second point gives you a good image of the battery’s high-current health.

10.5 volts is a typical decision point fir good-bad, but after several tests you will get a good feel for what is good and what is not.

Something like a 0.2 Ohm resistor capable of handling 500+ watts. Think an XX foot piece of # 12 wire.

Old school is a carbon-pile tester, but nobody uses them any more. Battery Beak.
